-- 
Oil Volatility Surges as Futures Touch $100 a Barrel on Libya

-- B y   M a r g o t   H a b i b y
-- 
2011-02-23T22:33:06Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-23/oil-volatility-surges-as-futures-touch-100-a-barrel-on-libya.html
Oil options volatility climbed as
the underlying futures touched $100 for the first time in more
than two years amid the violent uprising in  Libya .  Implied volatility for at-the-money options expiring in
April, a measure of expected price swings in futures and a gauge
of options prices, was 39.2 percent as of 4 p.m. in  New York , up
from 35.4 percent yesterday.  Oil for April delivery jumped $2.68, or 2.8 percent, to
$98.10 a barrel on the  New York Mercantile Exchange , the highest
settlement price since Oct. 1, 2008. Futures are up 24 percent
from a year ago.  April $120 calls were the most active options in electronic
trading today, with 8,836 lots changing hands. They gained 48
cents to 84 cents a barrel. April $100 calls, the next-most
active contract, increased $1.30 to $3.04 a barrel with 7,003
contracts trading. One contract covers 1,000 barrels of oil.  The six most active contracts were for April call options
at strike prices from $100 to $150.  Nymex distributes real-time data for electronic trading and
releases information on floor trading, where the bulk of options
trading occurs, the next business day.  April $125 calls were the most active options traded
yesterday, with 15,337 lots changing hands. They gained 21 cents
to 29 cents a barrel. The next-most active option, April $110
calls, increased 51 cents to 67 cents a barrel on 14,514
contracts.  Open interest was highest for April $100 calls with 43,027
contracts. Next were December $100 calls with 39,619 and May
$125 calls with 37,609.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Margot Habiby in  Dallas  at 
 mhabiby@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Bill Banker at   bbanker@bloomberg.net . 